metadata.name: golf #7
metadata.description:
This artwork is named 'golf' due to its structure and colors. The generated abstract and random pattern may evoke a golf course - the points symbolize the golf balls and the triangular shapes, the flag of each hole. The colors used, both calming and vibrant, recall the green grass of golf courses and the surrounding natural elements.

Press "s" to save a png

metadata.name: Make-believe #4
metadata.description:
#genuary32nd – Let's meet on this make-believe date, in this make-believe place.
I’m having déjà vu, or is it a memory?

This artwork is originally created for the genuary2023 prompt "Art Deco", using the same core algorithm as Memory Module. Made with fractal math and p5js.

Keyboard controls:
[s] Save the current view in live mode.
[1] to [8] Change resolution, 1.5K to 12K.
[g] Toggle texture.

URL params:
&aspect=[aspect ratio, eg 2]
&res=[resolution multiplier, 0.5-8]

Created by Elsif, 2023.02

metadata.name: Action; System #8
metadata.description:
Action; system is an experimental study inspired by the work of François Morellet. Morellet was one of the founders of the Groupe de Recherche d'Art Visuel (GRAV), founded in the 60s. His work was often informed by systems, a set of rules that determine the artwork, reducing the artist's subjectivity to a minimum.

This work explores what happens when we let go of the strict rule set. Do we ever fully let go?

-----------------
This work was released for the 2023 fundraising exhibition Cure3, and all of the proceeds and 1% of royalties will go to Parkinson's research funds. You can find more information at https://cure3.co.uk/.

-----------------
Controls
- R: new randomized output (the chances of recovering one of these outputs are very slim, that's what the next control is for)
- E: high-res output
- Double click: fullscreen

While you see the eye of Horus, your artwork is loading.

------------------
Made with p5.js & glsl

metadata.name: Dazers #3
metadata.description:
"Dazers": a digital art piece that feels like a visual road trip through the universe.

It's like watching radiant, spinning spheres pop up across the night sky, each one unique and temporary.

This creation brings an unexpected vibrancy to the vast, dark cosmos.

- HARCHI 2023

metadata.name: Sliders #23
metadata.description:
'Sliders' combines several geometric forms (including a '3D' representation of the cylinder) with a bright 'popping' color palette to create bold, abstract, geometric designs.

Creation: A series of colorfully illustrated layers (containing transparent regions) are stacked. Each layer is selected at random from several options. This means that each output is a unique artwork.

To download a 3150x3150px PNG:
Click/tap 'open', then click/tap the image to make a "Download image" button appear.

metadata.name: Lookouts #74
metadata.description:
Lookouts is a generative illustration done 100% in code using p5js. Inspired by my love for travel and minimalist design, this collection is built based on custom shapes filled with solid colors & limited texture.

The accompanying fxtext article (in ‘Mentions’ below) shares more details about the inspiration and development process of this project.

Lookouts renders as a fixed resolution output (2000 x 1666px). Controls (in live view): 
Press [4] to render at 4000 x 3333px
Press [8] to render at 8000 x 6666px
Press [s] to save the current view (default or higher resolution image)

metadata.name: StairWaves #171
metadata.description:
StairWaves is a generative collection imagining abstract stairs built in a wavy nature, with shadows being a key theme. While some waves are quite turbulent, others are just flat.

All shapes in the artwork are built using the same core logic applied in different ways. The method used to draw the waves is also used to draw the shadows, as well as the subtle textures on the surface of the waves. This homogeneous approach ensures a consistent and flowy feel to the final output.

StairWaves is coded entirely in p5.js. 

Controls (in live view): 
Press [2] to render 2000x2000px image
Press [4] to render 4000x4000px image
Press [s] to save the current view (default window size or 2000px or 4000px image)
